<h2 id="types-of-fibre">Types of Fibre</h2>
<ul>
<li>Natural Fibres: Obtained from animals &amp; plants</li>
<li>Synthetic: Man-made</li>
</ul>
<h2 id="animal-fibres">Animal Fibres</h2>
<ul>
<li>Wool: Obtained from sheep, goat, yak, llama, alpaca</li>
<li>Silk: From silkworm</li>
</ul>
<h3 id="wool">Wool</h3>
<ul>
<li>Obtained from hair of â€¦</li>
<li>Thick coat of hair</li>
<li>Uses:
<ul>
<li>Warm clothes</li>
<li>Carpets, upholstery</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Process:
<ol type="1">
<li>Fleece remove from sheep: shearing</li>
<li>Hair removed during hot weather</li>
<li>Sheep skin with hair is washed: scouring</li>
<li>Washed skin sent to factory</li>
<li>Sorted based on length, colour, etc.</li>
<li>Small fluffy fibres (aka burrs) are removed</li>
<li>Fibres are dyed</li>
<li>Fibres straightened and rolled into yarn</li>
</ol></li>
<li>Shearing does not hurt sheep</li>
<li>Indian breeds of sheep:</li>
</ul>
